@@ -0,0 +1,58 @@
+
+SoftCSA patch (using FFdecsa for descrambling)
+==============================================
+
+The SoftCSA patch implements software descrambling for budget cards. On full
+featured cards this is done on the hardware ECD chip.
+This version uses FFdecsa to descramble with very low CPU usage.
+
+NOTE: This is a highly experimental feature. Mostly not tested. Expect all
+kinds of bugs, crashes or weird behaviour. Any contributions to the code are
+welcome and I'm pretty sure you will find a place to publish them ...
+
+The SoftCSA function only works with budget cards (current DVB driver isn't
+able to deliver an encrypted stream on a full featured card).
+
+While the descrambling is done with this piece of code, you still need an
+additional plugin to capture and decrypt the CW from the ECM stream. You should
+first install this patch and then compile the plugin or the plugin won't enable
+SoftCSA support (sc 0.1.9+ only).
+
+This version of SoftCSA uses FFdecsa code to perform data descrambling.
+FFdecsa is very fast and doesn't need a fast CPU to work. If you CPU is able to
+decode MPEG in real time without being near 100% utilization, it is likely able
+to descramble too.
+
+There are a couple of things you should tune to optimize performance.
+
+1) The Makefile in the FFdecsa directory should use gcc options for your CPU;
+   you should change the "-march" flag to avoid slow speed or crashes.
+   Recent versions of gcc (3.3.3 or later is recommended) support: pentium,
+   pentium-mmx, pentiumpro, pentium2, pentium3, pentium4, k6, k6-2, k6-3,
+   athlon, athlon-tbird, athlon4, athlon-xp and athlon-mp. You could play
+   with other flags too, but it is not necessary (decreasing unrolling limit
+   may help older CPUs).
+
+2) You should edit FFdecsa.c to select the type of parallelism your CPU
+   supports and prefers from a performance point of view. If your CPU has MMX
+   support, try 64_MMX; if it hasn't or if you have compilation problems, try
+   32_INT. You have to edit the line near the "our choice" string.
+   Read the docs from FFdecsa for more information.
+
+The vdr Makefile tries to automatically build FFdecsa/FFdecsa.o, but it
+is recommend to compile FFdecsa before compiling vdr.
+The executable file named "FFdecsa/FFdecsa_test" will test the correctness and
+speed of FFdecsa.
+
+BUGS: we don't use the appropriate FFdecsa function to know how many packets we
+should put in one cluster, we just use an hardcoded number of 70, which is
+good with 64_MMX and other 64_* only. Change it to 36 for 32_* and 136 for 128_*.
+Using 70 with 128_* will seriously impact speed. You can find the right place
+to edit by searching for "HARDCODED" in device.c.
+
+History:
+--------
+
+17.09.2004: Version 0.255.0
+- Created first version based on FFdecsa-1.0.0.
+
